# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: saml-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] A **federated identity** in information technology is the means of linking a person's electronic identity and attributes, stored across multiple distinct identity management systems.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Federated identity is related to single sign-on (SSO), in which a user's single authentication ticket, or token, is trusted across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and is understood on the level of technical interoperability, and it would not be possible without some sort of federation.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] In information technology (IT), federated identity management (FIdM) amounts to having a common set of policies, practices and protocols in place to manage the identity and trust into IT users and devices across organizations.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Single sign-on (SSO) systems allow a single user authentication process across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and technical interoperability.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Centralized identity management solutions were created to help deal with user and data security where the user and the systems they accessed were within the same network – or at least the same "domain of control".
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Increasingly, however, users are accessing external systems which are fundamentally outside their domain of control, and external users are accessing internal systems.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] The increasingly common separation of the user from the systems requiring access is an inevitable by-product of the decentralization brought about by the integration of the Internet into every aspect of both personal and business life.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Evolving identity management challenges, and especially the challenges associated with cross-company, cross-domain access, have given rise to a new approach to identity management, known now as "federated identity management".
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] FIdM, or the "federation" of identity, describes the technologies, standards and use-cases which serve to enable the portability of identity information across otherwise autonomous security domains.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] The ultimate goal of identity federation is to enable users of one domain to securely access data or systems of another domain seamlessly, and without the need for completely redundant user administration.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Identity federation comes in many flavors, including "user-controlled" or "user-centric" scenarios, as well as enterprise-controlled or business-to-business scenarios.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Federation is enabled through the use of open industry standards and/or openly published specifications, such that multiple parties can achieve interoperability for common use-cases.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Typical use-cases involve things such as cross-domain, web-based single sign-on, cross-domain user account provisioning, cross-domain entitlement management and cross-domain user attribute exchange.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Use of identity federation standards can reduce cost by eliminating the need to scale one-off or proprietary solutions.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] It can increase security and lower risk by enabling an organization to identify and authenticate a user once, and then use that identity information across multiple systems, including external partner websites.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] It can improve privacy compliance by allowing the user to control what information is shared, or by limiting the amount of information shared.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] And lastly, it can drastically improve the end-user experience by eliminating the need for new account registration through automatic "federated provisioning" or the need to redundantly login through cross-domain single sign-on.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] The notion of identity federation is extremely broad, and also evolving.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] It could involve user-to-user and user-to-application as well as application-to-application use-case scenarios at both the browser tier and the web services or service-oriented architecture (SOA) tier.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] It can involve high-trust, high-security scenarios as well as low-trust, low-security scenarios.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] The levels of identity assurance that may be required for a given scenario are also being standardized through a common and open Identity Assurance Framework.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] It can involve user-centric use-cases, as well as enterprise-centric use-cases.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] The term "identity federation" is by design a generic term, and is not bound to any one specific protocol, technology, implementation or company.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Identity federations may be bi-lateral relationships or multilateral relationships.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] In the latter case, the multilateral federation frequently occurs in a vertical market, such as in law enforcement (such as the National Identity Exchange Federation - NIEF), and research and education (such as InCommon).
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] If the identity federation is bilateral, the two parties can exchange the necessary metadata (assertion signing keys, etc.) to implement the relationship.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] In a multilateral federation, the metadata exchange among participants is a more complex issue.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] It can be handled in a hub-and-spoke exchange or by the distribution of a metadata aggregate by a federated operator.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] One thing that is consistent, however, is the fact that "federation" describes methods of identity portability which are achieved in an open, often standards-based manner – meaning anyone adhering to the open specification or standard can achieve the full spectrum of use-cases and interoperability.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Identity federation can be accomplished any number of ways, some of which involve the use of formal Internet standards, such as the OASIS Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) specification, and some of which may involve open-source technologies and/or other openly published specifications (e.g.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Information Cards, OpenID, the Higgins trust framework or Novell's Bandit project).
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Technologies used for federated identity include SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language), OAuth, OpenID, Security Tokens (Simple Web Tokens, JSON Web Tokens, and SAML assertions), Web Service Specifications, and Windows Identity Foundation.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] The Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program (FedRAMP) is a government-wide program that provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud products and services.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] The FedRAMP program supports the transition of federal agencies from legacy IT infrastructure to cloud-based computing environments.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Here is a list of services that provide social login features which they encourage other websites to use.
[src:saml-security/federated-identity] Related are federated identity login providers.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The OpenID standard provides a framework for the communication that must take place between the identity provider and the OpenID acceptor (the "relying party").
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] An extension to the standard (the OpenID Attribute Exchange) facilitates the transfer of user attributes, such as name and gender, from the OpenID identity provider to the relying party (each relying party may request a different set of attributes, depending on its requirements).
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The OpenID protocol does not rely on a central authority to authenticate a user's identity.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Moreover, neither services nor the OpenID standard may mandate a specific means by which to authenticate users, allowing for approaches ranging from the common (such as passwords) to the novel (such as smart cards or biometrics).
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The final version of OpenID is OpenID 2.0, finalized and published in December 2007.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The term *OpenID* may also refer to an identifier as specified in the OpenID standard; these identifiers take the form of a unique Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), and are managed by some "OpenID provider" that handles authentication.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Facebook did use OpenID in the past, but moved to Facebook Connect.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Blogger also used OpenID, but since May 2018 no longer supports it.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] OpenID is a decentralized authentication protocol that allows users to authenticate with multiple websites using a single set of credentials, eliminating the need for separate usernames and passwords for each website.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] OpenID authenticates a user with an identity provider (IdP), who then provides the user with a unique identifier (called an OpenID).
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] This identifier can then be used to authenticate the user with any website that supports OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] When a user visits a website that supports OpenID authentication, the website will redirect the user to their chosen IdP.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The IdP will then prompt the user to authenticate themselves (e.g., by entering a username and password).
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Once the user is authenticated, the IdP will generate an OpenID and send it back to the website.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The website can then use this OpenID to authenticate the user without needing to know their actual credentials.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] OpenID is built on top of several existing standards, including HTTP, HTML, and XML.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] OpenID relies on a number of technologies, including a discovery mechanism that allows websites to find the IdP associated with a particular OpenID, as well as security mechanisms to protect against phishing and other attacks.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] One of the key benefits of OpenID is that it allows users to control their own identity information, rather than relying on individual websites to store and manage their login credentials.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] This can be particularly important in cases where websites are vulnerable to security breaches or where users are concerned about the privacy of their personal information.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] OpenID has been widely adopted by a number of large websites and service providers, including Google, Yahoo!, and PayPal.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The protocol is also used by a number of open source projects and frameworks, including Ruby on Rails and Django.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The end user interacts with a relying party (such as a website) that provides an option to specify an OpenID for the purposes of authentication; an end user typically has previously registered an OpenID (e.g.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] `alice.openid.example.org`) with an OpenID provider (e.g.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The relying party typically transforms the OpenID into a canonical URL form (e.g.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The `checkid_immediate` mode can fall back to the `checkid_setup` mode if the operation cannot be automated.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] First, the relying party and the OpenID provider (optionally) establish a shared secret, referenced by an *associate handle*, which the relying party then stores.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] If using the `checkid_setup` mode, the relying party redirects the end user's user-agent to the OpenID provider so the end user can authenticate directly with the OpenID provider.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The method of authentication may vary, but typically, an OpenID provider prompts the end user for a password or some cryptographic token, and then asks whether the end user trusts the relying party to receive the necessary identity details.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] If the end user declines the OpenID provider's request to trust the relying party, then the user-agent is redirected back to the relying party with a message indicating that authentication was rejected; the relying party in turn refuses to authenticate the end user.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] If the end user accepts the OpenID provider's request to trust the relying party, then the user-agent is redirected back to the relying party along with the end user's credentials.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] That relying party must then confirm that the credentials really came from the OpenID provider.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In contrast, a *stateless* or *dumb* relying party must make one more background request (`check_authentication`) to ensure that the data indeed came from the OpenID provider.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] After the OpenID has been verified, authentication is considered successful and the end user is considered logged into the relying party under the identity specified by the given OpenID (e.g.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The relying party typically then stores the end user's OpenID along with the end user's other session information.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] To obtain an OpenID-enabled URL that can be used to log into OpenID-enabled websites, a user registers an OpenID identifier with an identity provider.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Identity providers offer the ability to register a URL (typically a third-level domain, e.g. username.example.com) that will automatically be configured with OpenID authentication service.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Once they have registered an OpenID, a user can also use an existing URL under their own control (such as a blog or home page) as an alias or "delegated identity".
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] They simply insert the appropriate OpenID tags in the HTML or serve a Yadis document.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Starting with OpenID Authentication 2.0 (and some 1.1 implementations), there are two types of identifiers that can be used with OpenID: URLs and XRIs.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] XRIs are a new form of Internet identifier designed specifically for cross-domain digital identity.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] For example, XRIs come in two forms—i-names and i-numbers—that are usually registered simultaneously as synonyms.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] I-names are reassignable (like domain names), while i-numbers are never reassigned.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] When an XRI i-name is used as an OpenID identifier, it is immediately resolved to the synonymous i-number (the CanonicalID element of the XRDS document).
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] This i-number is the OpenID identifier stored by the relying party.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In this way, both the user and the relying party are protected from the end user's OpenID identity ever being taken over by another party as can happen with a URL based on a reassignable DNS name.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation (OIDF) promotes and enhances the OpenID community and technologies.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The OIDF is a non-profit international standards development organization of individual developers, government agencies and companies who wish to promote and protect OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation was formed in June 2007 and serves as a public trust organization representing an open community of developers, vendors and users.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] OIDF assists the community by providing needed infrastructure and help in promoting and supporting adoption of OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] This includes managing intellectual property and trade marks as well a fostering viral growth and global participation in OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] OIDF is a global organization to promote digital identity and to encourage the further adoption of OpenID, the OIDF has encouraged the creation of member chapters.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Member chapters are officially part of the Foundation and work within their own constituency to support the development and adoption of OpenID as a framework for user-centric identity on the internet.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The OIDF ensures that OpenID specifications are freely implementable therefore the OIDF requires all contributors to sign a contribution agreement.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] This agreement both grants a copyright license to the Foundation to publish the collective specifications and includes a patent non-assertion agreement.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The non-assertion agreement states that the contributor will not sue someone for implementing OpenID specifications.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The OpenID trademark in the United States was assigned to the OpenID Foundation in March 2008.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] It had been registered by NetMesh Inc. before the OpenID Foundation was operational.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In Europe, as of August 31, 2007, the OpenID trademark is registered to the OpenID Europe Foundation.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The OpenID logo was designed by Randy "ydnar" Reddig, who in 2005 had expressed plans to transfer the rights to an OpenID organization.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Sun Microsystems, VeriSign and a number of smaller companies involved in OpenID have issued patent non-assertion covenants covering OpenID 1.1 specifications.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The covenants state that the companies will not assert any of their patents against OpenID implementations and will revoke their promises from anyone who threatens, or asserts, patents against OpenID implementors.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In March, 2012, a research paper reported two generic security issues in OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Both issues allow an attacker to sign in to a victim's relying party accounts.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] For the first issue, OpenID and Google (an Identity Provider of OpenID) both published security advisories to address it.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Google's advisory says "An attacker could forge an OpenID request that doesn't ask for the user's email address, and then insert an unsigned email address into the IdPs response.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] If the attacker relays this response to a website that doesn't notice that this attribute is unsigned, the website may be tricked into logging the attacker in to any local account." The research paper claims that many popular websites have been confirmed vulnerable, including Yahoo!
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Mail, smartsheet.com, Zoho, manymoon.com, diigo.com.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The researchers have notified the affected parties, who have then fixed their vulnerable code.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] For the second issue, the paper called it "Data Type Confusion Logic Flaw", which also allows attackers to sign in to victims' RP accounts.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Google and PayPal were initially confirmed vulnerable.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] OpenID published a vulnerability report on the flaw.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The report says Google and PayPal have applied fixes, and suggest other OpenID vendors to check their implementations.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Some observers have suggested that OpenID has security weaknesses and may prove vulnerable to phishing attacks.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] For example, a malicious relaying party may forward the end user to a bogus identity provider authentication page asking that end user to input their credentials.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] On completion of this, the malicious party (who in this case also controls the bogus authentication page) could then have access to the end user's account with the identity provider, and then use that end user's OpenID to log into other services.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In an attempt to combat possible phishing attacks, some OpenID providers mandate that the end user needs to be authenticated with them prior to an attempt to authenticate with the relying party.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] This relies on the end user knowing the policy of the identity provider.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Other security issues identified with OpenID involve lack of privacy and failure to address the trust problem.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] However, this problem is not unique to OpenID and is simply the state of the Internet as commonly used.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The Identity Provider does, however, get a log of your OpenID logins; they know when you logged into what website, making cross-site tracking much easier.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] A compromised OpenID account is also likely to be a more serious breach of privacy than a compromised account on a single site.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Another important vulnerability is present in the last step in the authentication scheme when TLS/SSL are not used: the redirect-URL from the identity provider to the relying party.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The problem with this redirect is the fact that anyone who can obtain this URL (e.g. by sniffing the wire) can replay it and get logged into the site as the victim user.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Some of the identity providers use nonces (a number used just once) to allow a user to log into the site once and fail all the consecutive attempts.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The nonce solution works if the user is the first one to use the URL.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] However, a fast attacker who is sniffing the wire can obtain the URL and immediately reset a user's TCP connection (as an attacker is sniffing the wire and knows the required TCP sequence numbers) and then execute the replay attack as described above.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Thus nonces only protect against passive attackers, but cannot prevent active attackers from executing the replay attack.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Use of TLS/SSL in the authentication process can significantly reduce this risk.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] On May 1, 2014, a bug dubbed "Covert Redirect related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" was disclosed.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] It was discovered by mathematics doctoral student Wang Jing at the School of Physical and Mathematical Sciences, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The announcement of OpenID is: "'Covert Redirect', publicized in May 2014, is an instance of attackers using open redirectors – a well-known threat, with well-known means of prevention.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] "The general consensus, so far, is that Covert Redirect is not as bad, but still a threat.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] A patch was not immediately made available.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Ori Eisen, founder, chairman and chief innovation officer at 41st Parameter told Sue Marquette Poremba, "In any distributed system, we are counting of the good nature of the participants to do the right thing.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In cases like OAuth and OpenID, the distribution is so vast that it is unreasonable to expect each and every website to patch up in the near future".
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The original OpenID authentication protocol was developed in May 2005 by Brad Fitzpatrick, creator of popular community website LiveJournal, while working at Six Apart.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Initially referred to as Yadis (an acronym for "Yet another distributed identity system"), it was named OpenID after the openid.net domain name was given to Six Apart to use for the project.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] OpenID support was soon implemented on LiveJournal and fellow LiveJournal engine community DeadJournal for blog post comments and quickly gained attention in the digital identity community.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Web developer JanRain was an early supporter of OpenID, providing OpenID software libraries and expanding its business around OpenID-based services.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In late June, discussions started between OpenID users and developers from enterprise software company NetMesh, leading to collaboration on interoperability between OpenID and NetMesh's similar Light-weight Identity (LID) protocol.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The direct result of the collaboration was the Yadis discovery protocol, adopting the name originally used for OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The new Yadis was announced on October 24, 2005.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] After a discussion at the 2005 Internet Identity Workshop a few days later, XRI/i-names developers joined the Yadis project, contributing their Extensible Resource Descriptor Sequence (XRDS) format for utilization in the protocol.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In December, developers at Sxip Identity began discussions with the OpenID/Yadis community after announcing a shift in the development of version 2.0 of its Simple Extensible Identity Protocol (SXIP) to URL-based identities like LID and OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In March 2006, JanRain developed a Simple Registration (SREG) extension for OpenID enabling primitive profile-exchange and in April submitted a proposal to formalize extensions to OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The same month, work had also begun on incorporating full XRI support into OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Around early May, key OpenID developer David Recordon left Six Apart, joining VeriSign to focus more on digital identity and guidance for the OpenID spec.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] By early June, the major differences between the SXIP 2.0 and OpenID projects were resolved with the agreement to support multiple personas in OpenID by submission of an identity provider URL rather than a full identity URL.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Late in 2006, a ZDNet opinion piece made the case for OpenID to users, web site operators and entrepreneurs.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] On January 31, 2007, Symantec announced support for OpenID in its Identity Initiative products and services.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] A week later, on February 6 Microsoft made a joint announcement with JanRain, Sxip, and VeriSign to collaborate on interoperability between OpenID and Microsoft's Windows CardSpace digital identity platform, with particular focus on developing a phishing-resistant authentication solution for OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] As part of the collaboration, Microsoft pledged to support OpenID in its future identity server products and JanRain, Sxip, and VeriSign pledged to add support for Microsoft's Information Card profile to their future identity solutions.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In mid-February, AOL announced that an experimental OpenID provider service was functional for all AOL and AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) accounts.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In May, Sun Microsystems began working with the OpenID community, announcing an OpenID program, as well as entering a non-assertion covenant with the OpenID community, pledging not to assert any of its patents against implementations of OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In June, OpenID leadership formed the OpenID Foundation, an Oregon-based public benefit corporation for managing the OpenID brand and property.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The same month, an independent OpenID Europe Foundation was formed in Belgium by Snorri Giorgetti.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] By early December, non-assertion agreements were collected by the major contributors to the protocol and the final OpenID Authentication 2.0 and OpenID Attribute Exchange 1.0 specifications were ratified on December 5.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In mid-January 2008, Yahoo! announced initial OpenID 2.0 support, both as a provider and as a relying party, releasing the provider service by the end of the month.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In early February, Google, IBM, Microsoft, VeriSign and Yahoo! joined the OpenID Foundation as corporate board members.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Around early May, SourceForge, Inc. introduced OpenID provider and relying party support to leading open source software development website SourceForge.net.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In late July, popular social network service MySpace announced support for OpenID as a provider.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In late October, Google launched support as an OpenID provider and Microsoft announced that Windows Live ID would support OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In November, JanRain announced a free hosted service, RPX Basic, that allows websites to begin accepting OpenIDs for registration and login without having to install, integrate and configure the OpenID open source libraries.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In January 2009, PayPal joined the OpenID Foundation as a corporate member, followed shortly by Facebook in February.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation formed an executive committee and appointed Don Thibeau as executive director.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In March, MySpace launched their previously announced OpenID provider service, enabling all MySpace users to use their MySpace URL as an OpenID.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In May, Facebook launched their relying party functionality, letting users use an automatic login-enabled OpenID account (e.g.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In September 2013, Janrain announced that MyOpenID.com would be shut down on February 1, 2014; a pie chart showed Facebook and Google dominate the social login space as of Q2 2013.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Facebook has since left OpenID; it is no longer a sponsor, represented on the board, or permitting OpenID logins.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In May 2016, Symantec announced that they would be discontinuing their pip.verisignlabs.com OpenID personal identity portal service.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In March 2018, Stack Overflow announced an end to OpenID support, citing insufficient usage to justify the cost.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In the announcement, it was stated that based on activity, users strongly preferred Facebook, Google, and e-mail/password based account authentication.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] OpenID is a way to use a single set of user credentials to access multiple sites, while OAuth facilitates the authorization of one site to access and use information related to the user's account on another site.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Although OAuth is not an authentication protocol, it can be used as part of one.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The following drawing highlights the differences between using OpenID versus OAuth for authentication.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Note that with OpenID, the process starts with the application asking the user for their identity (typically an OpenID URI), whereas in the case of OAuth, the application directly requests a limited access OAuth Token (valet key) to access the APIs (enter the house) on user's behalf.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] If the user can grant that access, the application can retrieve the unique identifier for establishing the profile (identity) using the APIs.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] OpenID provides a cryptographic verification mechanism that prevents the attack below against users who misuse OAuth for authentication.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Note that the valet key does not describe the user in any way, it only provides limited access rights, to some house (which is not even necessarily the user's, they just had a key).
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Therefore if the key becomes compromised (the user is malicious and managed to steal the key to someone else's house), then the user can impersonate the house owner to the application who requested their authenticity.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] If the key is compromised by any point in the chain of trust, a malicious user may intercept it and use it to impersonate user X for any application relying on OAuth2 for pseudo authentication against the same OAuth authorization server.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Conversely, the notarized letter contains the user's signature, which can be checked by the requesting application against the user, so this attack is not viable.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The letter can use public-key cryptography to be authenticated.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] Published in February 2014 by the OpenID Foundation, OpenID Connect (OIDC) is the third generation of OpenID technology.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] It is an authentication layer on top of the OAuth 2.0 authorization framework.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] It allows computing clients to verify the identity of an end user based on the authentication performed by an authorization server, as well as to obtain the basic profile information about the end user in an interoperable and REST-like manner.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] In technical terms, OpenID Connect specifies a RESTful HTTP API, using JSON as a data format.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] OpenID Connect allows a range of parties, including web-based, mobile and JavaScript clients, to request and receive information about authenticated sessions and end users.
[src:saml-security/openid-connect] The OpenID Connect specification is extensible, supporting optional features such as encryption of identity data, discovery of OpenID providers, and session management.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Some 30 individuals from more than 24 companies and organizations were involved in the creation of SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] In particular, and of special note, Liberty Alliance donated its Identity Federation Framework (ID-FF) specification to OASIS, which became the basis of the SAML 2.0 specification.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Thus SAML 2.0 represents the convergence of SAML 1.1, Liberty ID-FF 1.2 Archived 2021-02-24 at the Wayback Machine, and Shibboleth 1.3.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] An assertion is a package of information that supplies zero or more statements made by a SAML authority.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] SAML assertions are usually made about a subject, represented by the `<Subject>` element.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The SAML 2.0 specification defines three different kinds of assertion statements that can be created by a SAML authority.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] All SAML-defined statements are associated with a subject.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] An important type of SAML assertion is the so-called "bearer" assertion used to facilitate Web Browser SSO.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Here is an example of a short-lived bearer assertion issued by an identity provider (https://idp.example.org/SAML2) to a service provider (https://sp.example.com/SAML2).
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The assertion includes both an Authentication Assertion `<saml:AuthnStatement>` and an Attribute Assertion `<saml:AttributeStatement>`, which presumably the service provider uses to make an access control decision.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The prefix `saml:` represents the SAML V2.0 assertion namespace.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The most important of these protocols—the Authentication Request Protocol—is discussed in detail below.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] In SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO Profiles are initiated by the Identity Provider (IDP), that is, an unsolicited `<samlp:Response>` element is transmitted from the identity provider to the service provider (via the browser).
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] In SAML 2.0, however, the flow begins at the service provider who issues an explicit authentication request to the identity provider.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The resulting *Authentication Request Protocol* is a significant new feature of SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The above `<samlp:AuthnRequest>` element, which implicitly requests an assertion containing an authentication statement, was evidently issued by a service provider (https://sp.example.com/SAML2) and subsequently presented to the identity provider (via the browser).
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The identity provider authenticates the principal (if necessary) and issues an authentication response, which is transmitted back to the service provider (again via the browser).
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] A SAML message is transmitted from one entity to another either *by value* or *by reference*.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] A reference to a SAML message is called an *artifact*.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The receiver of an artifact resolves the reference by sending a `<samlp:ArtifactResolve>` request directly to the issuer of the artifact, who then responds with the actual message referenced by the artifact.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] In response, the service provider returns the SAML element referenced by the enclosed artifact.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] This protocol forms the basis of the HTTP Artifact Binding.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] For Web Browser SSO, the HTTP Redirect Binding and the HTTP POST Binding are commonly used.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] For example, the service provider may use HTTP Redirect to send a request while the identity provider uses HTTP POST to transmit the response.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] This example illustrates that an entity's choice of binding is independent of its partner's choice of binding.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] SAML protocol messages can be carried directly in the URL query string of an HTTP GET request.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Since the length of URLs is limited in practice, the HTTP Redirect binding is suitable for short messages, such as the `<samlp:AuthnRequest>` message.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Longer messages (e.g. those containing signed or encrypted SAML assertions, such as SAML Responses) are usually transmitted via other bindings such as the HTTP POST Binding.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] SAML requests or responses transmitted via HTTP Redirect have a `SAMLRequest` or `SAMLResponse` query string parameter, respectively.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Before it's sent, the message is deflated (without header and checksum), base64-encoded, and URL-encoded, in that order.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Upon receipt, the process is reversed to recover the original message.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The above message (formatted for readability) may be signed for additional security.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] In practice, all the data contained in a `<samlp:AuthnRequest>`, such as `Issuer` which contains the SP ID, and `NameIDPolicy`, has been agreed between IdP and SP beforehand (via manual information exchange or via SAML metadata).
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] In that case signing the request is not a security constraint.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] When the `<samlp:AuthnRequest>` contains information not known by the IdP beforehand, such as Assertion Consumer Service URL, signing the request is recommended for security purposes.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] In the following example, both the service provider and the identity provider use an HTTP POST binding.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The value of the `SAMLRequest` parameter is the base64-encoding of a `<samlp:AuthnRequest>` element, which is transmitted to the identity provider via the browser.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The value of the `SAMLResponse` parameter is the base64 encoding of a `<samlp:Response>` element, which likewise is transmitted to the service provider via the browser.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] This assumes, of course, that the first form element in the page contains the above SAMLResponse containing `form` element (`forms[0]`).
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The HTTP Artifact Binding uses the Artifact Resolution Protocol and the SAML SOAP Binding (over HTTP) to resolve a SAML message by reference.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Consider the following specific example.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Suppose a service provider wants to send a `<samlp:AuthnRequest>` message to an identity provider.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Next the identity provider sends a `<samlp:ArtifactResolve>` request (such as the ArtifactResolveRequest shown earlier) directly to the service provider via a back channel.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Of course the flow can go in the other direction as well, that is, the identity provider may issue an artifact, and in fact this is more common.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] See, for example, the "double artifact" profile example later in this topic.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Thus a SAML 2.0 artifact consists of three components: a two-byte `TypeCode`, a two-byte `EndpointIndex`, and an arbitrary sequence of bytes called the `RemainingArtifact`.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] These three pieces of information are concatenated and base64-encoded to yield the complete artifact.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The `TypeCode` uniquely identifies the artifact format.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] SAML 2.0 predefines just one such artifact, of type 0x0004.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The `EndpointIndex` is a reference to a particular artifact resolution endpoint managed by the artifact issuer (which may be either the IdP or the SP, as mentioned earlier).
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The `RemainingArtifact`, which is determined by the type definition, is the "meat" of the artifact.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] Thus a type 0x0004 artifact is of size 44 bytes (unencoded).
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The `SourceId` is an arbitrary sequence of bytes, although in practice, the `SourceId` is the SHA-1 hash of the issuer's entityID.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The `MessageHandle` is a random sequence of bytes that references a SAML message that the artifact issuer is willing to produce on-demand.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] If you look closely, you can see the `TypeCode` (0x0004) and the `EndpointIndex` (0x0000) at the front of the artifact.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The next 20 bytes are the SHA-1 hash of the issuer's entityID (https://idp.example.org/SAML2) followed by 20 random bytes.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p01] The base64-encoding of these 44 bytes is what you see in the ArtifactResolveRequest example above.
