[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] As a hypothetical example of a *Common Domain*, let's suppose Example UK (example.co.uk) and Example Deutschland (example.de) belong to the virtual organization Example Global Alliance (example.com).
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] In this example, the domain **example.com** is the common domain.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] Both Example UK and Example Deutschland have a presence in this domain (uk.example.com and de.example.com, resp.).
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] The *Common Domain Cookie* is a secure browser cookie scoped to the common domain.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] For each browser user, this cookie stores a history list of recently visited IdPs.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] The name and value of the cookie are specified in the IdP Discovery Profile (SAMLProf).
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] After a successful act of authentication, the IdP requests the *Common Domain Cookie Writing Service*.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] This service appends the IdP's unique identifier to the common domain cookie.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] The SP, when it receives an unauthenticated request for a protected resource, requests the *Common Domain Cookie Reading Service* to discover the browser user's most recently used IdP.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] The SAML SOAP binding is often used in conjunction with queries.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] The *Attribute Query* is perhaps the most important type of SAML query.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] Often a requester, acting on behalf of the principal, queries an identity provider for attributes.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] Note that the `Issuer` is the `Subject` in this case.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] This is sometimes called an *attribute self-query*.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] In contrast to the BearerAssertion shown earlier, this assertion has a longer lifetime corresponding to the lifetime of the X.509 certificate that the principal used to authenticate to the identity provider.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] Moreover, since the assertion is signed, the user can push this assertion to a relying party, and as long as the user can prove possession of the corresponding private key (hence the name "holder-of-key"), the relying party can be assured that the assertion is authentic.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] Quite literally, metadata is what makes SAML work (or work well).
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] Metadata ensures a secure transaction between an identity provider and a service provider.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] Before metadata, trust information was encoded into the implementation in a proprietary manner.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] Now the sharing of trust information is facilitated by standard metadata.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] SAML 2.0 provides a well-defined, interoperable metadata format that entities can leverage to bootstrap the trust process.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] By definition, an identity provider manages an SSO service that supports the SAML Web Browser SSO profile specified in SAMLProf.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] See, for example, the identity provider described in the `<md:IDPSSODescriptor>` element shown in the next section.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] The previous metadata element describes the SSO service at the identity provider.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] As noted at the beginning of this section, the values of the `Location` attributes are used by a service provider to route SAML messages, which minimizes the possibility of a rogue identity provider orchestrating a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] By definition, a service provider manages an assertion consumer service that supports the SAML Web Browser SSO profile specified in SAMLProf.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] See, for example, the service provider described in the `<md:SPSSODescriptor>` element shown in the next section.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] As noted at the beginning of this section, the values of the `Location` attributes are used by an identity provider to route SAML messages, which minimizes the possibility of a rogue service provider orchestrating a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] In the previous examples, each `<md:EntityDescriptor>` element is shown to be digitally signed.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] Typically metadata aggregates are published by trusted third parties called *federations* who vouch for the integrity of all the metadata in the aggregate.
[src:saml-security/saml-2-0-p02] Note that metadata aggregates can be very large, composed of hundreds or even thousands of entities per aggregate.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The **S**ecurity **A**ssertion **M**arkup **L**anguage (SAML) is an open standard for exchanging authorization and authentication information.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The *Web Browser SAML/SSO Profile with Redirect/POST bindings* is one of the most common SSO implementation.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This cheatsheet will focus primarily on that profile.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] TLS 1.2 is the most common solution to guarantee message confidentiality and integrity at the transport layer.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Refer to SAML Security (section 4.2.1) for additional information.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] A digitally signed message with a certified key is the most common solution to guarantee message integrity and authentication.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Refer to SAML Security (section 4.3) for additional information.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Assertions may be encrypted via XMLEnc to prevent disclosure of sensitive attributes post transportation.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Refer to SAML Security (section 4.2.2) for additional information.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is a common area for security gaps - see Google SSO vulnerability for a real life example.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Their SSO profile was vulnerable to a Man-in-the-middle attack from a malicious SP (Service Provider).
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The SSO Web Browser Profile is most susceptible to attacks from trusted partners.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This particular security flaw was exposed because the SAML Response did not contain all of the required data elements necessary for a secure message exchange.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Following the SAML Profile usage requirements for AuthnRequest (4.1.4.1) and Response (4.1.4.2) will help counter this attack.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Vulnerabilities in SAML implementations due to XML Signature Wrapping attacks were described in 2012, On Breaking SAML: Be Whoever You Want to Be.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is another common area for security gaps simply because of the vast number of steps to assert.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Revisit each security threat that exists within the SAML Security document and assert you have applied the appropriate countermeasures for threats that may exist for your particular implementation.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The SAML technical overview contains the most complete diagrams.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] For the Web Browser SSO Profile with Redirect/POST bindings refer to the section 4.1.3.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In fact, of all the SAML documentation, the technical overview is the most valuable from a high-level perspective.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Unsolicited Response is inherently less secure by design due to the lack of **login CSRF** protection.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This limitation arises because the Service Provider (SP) has no opportunity to create a pre-login session or verify that the authentication request was intentionally initiated by the user.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] While this design does not make IdP-initiated SSO uniquely vulnerable to Man-in-the-Middle (MITM) attacks—those risks apply equally to SP-initiated flows if transport security is compromised—it does remove an important layer of login intent validation.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Despite these concerns, IdP-initiated SSO remains supported for backward compatibility (notably with SAML 1.1).
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The SAML protocol is rarely the attack vector of choice, though it's important to have cheatsheets to make sure that this is robust.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The various endpoints are more targeted, so how the SAML token is generated and how it is consumed are both important in practice.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Typically the security association between the Identity Provider (IdP) and Service Provider (SP) is created when the SP explicitly chooses to trust the IdP's X.509 signing certificate.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Exactly how this occurs can have a strong bearing on overall security posture.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In many cases, the method of manually setting the association is akin to Certificate Pinning, which is not ideal.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Depending on the IdP and SP software, or various design considerations, this may be unavoidable.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Keep in mind that the certificate's signature type can be different from that of the XML document signing type.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The certificate's corresponding private key is the only key that can be used to sign the XML document, but the signing algorithm is chosen at the IdP's discretion.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The most commonly supported signing algorithm is rsa-sha256.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The most common SAML use cases are those of business-to-business (B2B).
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This means that the two parties have different security polices, practices, and risk tolerances.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This guidance focuses mainly on the B2B use case.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] However SAML based federation or SSO is commonly used inside of an organization.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In this case the term third-party CA does not apply.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] It is likely that the CA has been built and run to company standards and it poses no more or less risk to the SAML systems.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The term third-party CA is meant to indicate a private CA run by a third-party.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] There are actually 5 separate use cases for certificates in a SAML system.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] While this document mainly talks about the IdP’s SAML signing certificate, the security considerations apply to all four SAML related certificates.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The fifth certificate, the IdP’s TLS server certificate is no more or less special than any other server certificate.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is the certificate that an SP uses to validate an IdD’s SAML response.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The IdP signs that response with the certificate’s corresponding private key.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is often the most important certificate and private key, as this protects the identity assertions being sent to the SP.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is less commonly used, as this is used when the SP wants to protect the SAML request sent to the IdP, not just from tampering, but from information disclosure.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] There should be no sensitive information in the SAML request, so it is less commonly used.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If used, the certificate and private key must be different from that of the SAML signing certificate.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] It is a best practice, though not required, that SPs and IdPs not allow IdP Initiated SSO.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This means that the caller starts their SAML flow at the SP, which produces a signed SAML request intended for the IdP.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] It is a best practice to avoid placing sensitive data in the IdP’s SAML response, but sometimes it is unavoidable.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] When information disclosure is a consideration, an SP will have a SAML encryption certificate.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The IdP will use this and the embedded public key, in order to encrypt the SAML response.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The SP must use a separate certificate and key pair for SAML signing and encryption.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In the context of SAML signing and encryption, X.509 certificates are most often treated simply as a wrapper to hold a public key that is used to verify a signature, or to wrap a symmetric key for SAML encryption.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Nonetheless, a certificate can contain attributes that can be used to further enhance security.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] OWASP recommends that IdPs and SPs move to adopt the EKU, KU, and key lifetimes mentioned below.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] These legitimately enhance security and allow the verifying party to further protect themselves.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] They also help show compliance with PKI norms.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The key pair size and type and signing algorithm choice has strong bearing on security and interoperability.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Not all IdP and SP software packages or libraries support all combinations of options.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] As one IdP often has many SPs associated with it, the only option is to pick the least secure option that is still considered secure.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The most supported and currently secure combination is using RSA 2048 bit keys and SHA-256 hashing/signing.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is referring to the certificate’s signing algorithm and not the SAML XML signing.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] As post-quantum algorithms become more prevalent, and ultimately required, this becomes even more complex.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Those writing SAML SP and IdP software should begin looking at options to support more key and signing algorithms.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] ECC Keys can be much smaller while providing more security than RSA keys and the math involved is faster to perform.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] These are preferred when all parties can use them.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] ECC keys can be as low as 256 bit and still be secure.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The minimum RSA key size should be 2048 bit.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] At least one major vendor Microsoft Entra doesn’t support ECC keys.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] When public key cryptography is used for signing data, the data is first hashed with an chosen algorithm and then the hash is signed using the private key.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] No IdP should use SHA-1 as the certificate signing hash.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] That said, if possible moving to larger hash algorithms like SHA-384 or SHA-512 means you are better future-proofing your service.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In this context we are talking about the certificate’s signing algorithm and not the one used to sign the SAML response XML.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Certificates contain a NotBefore and NotOnorAfter attribute.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Most IdPs ignore these in favor of guaranteeing uptime if certificate rotation does not happen on time.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The SAML certificate lifetime should be handled well enough that ignoring these is not needed.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Ignoring the certificate's validity period is fundamentally a bad idea.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] 5) allows RSA 2048 bit keys to last for 3 years, the maximum lifetime of a SAML signing certificate should be two years.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If the private key is not well protected, such as in a Hardware Security Module (HSM), that may be too long to be safe.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] EKU describes a specific use case that the certificate is intended for.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] These are use cases like server authentication, client authentication, and code signing, which are not appropriate for SAML signing.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] There is no widely accepted EKU for SAML signing, but RFC 9336 defines one that is ideal, id-kp-documentSigning (1.3.6.1.5.5.7.3.36).
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] IdPs and SPs may consider standardizing on this EKU.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] KU describes the underlying cryptographic operations that the private key is meant for.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] There are things like digitalSignature, nonRepudiation, keyEncipherment, etc.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] IdPs and SPs may consider requiring digitalSignature and further, disallowing certificates that have other KUs, as certificates should only be used for one use case. e.g. the IdP's TLS server certificate must never be the SAML signing certificate.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Certificate Revocation List (CRL) Distribution Point are a list of certificates that the CA says should no longer be trusted.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] They are most often delivered over HTTP and the CRL URLs are generally embedded in each CA issued certificate.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The CRL is signed by the CA, so a man-in-the-middle attack against the HTTP cannot harm the integrity of the list, other than to tamper with, and thus invalidate, it.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] That is, it can't be altered by an attacker.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Only CA signed certificates can have a CRL.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If the SAML certificate has a CRL listed, it should be reachable by the validating party and the party should validate it.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Considering the level of risk, if a private key is compromised, and the smaller scale of IdP to SP relationships, parties in a SAML system should establish a plan with contact lists to notify and rotate certificates rapidly in case of an incident.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Many SAML products and libraries don’t support revocation checking, and simply revoking the certificate, without coordinated replacement, means there is an outage.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] OCSP is another way of checking to see if a certificate is revoked.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The OCSP URL is embedded in the certificate , like a CRL, and should be reachable over HTTP.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The response is signed, so MITM attacks are not an integrity concern.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] OCSP is becoming less favored, as the exchange creates privacy concerns.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The caller's IP address can be seen and the certificate that is being used is disclosed.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is less of a concern for SAML, as this does not disclose a destination website, use overall has declined.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If an OCSP URL is present on any certificate in the chain, it should be used to check if the certificate is revoked.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The SAML signing certificate can be signed by one of three things.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The certificate can be self-signed, public CA signed, or private CA signed.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Each has pros and cons, however, given the current state of WebPKI (public) and private PKI, using self-signed SAML certificates are the clear winner when proper precautions are taken for exchanging the certificates.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] All X.509 certificates are signed, using a private key, by an authority known as an Issuer.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This may be a CA or in the case of a self-signed certificate the certificate's corresponding private key.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In the case of a CA signed certificate, the signer may also have a certificate that has an Issuer, and so on.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is called chain, or path, and should terminate in a Root CA (which is self-signed by definition).
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If the issuer is a CA, its attributes, such as EKU, KU, and CRLs, may also be validated.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This should happen for each certificate in the path all the way to the root.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] With this certificate type, a Public CA issues the certificate, in accordance with their rules and the rules of the CA Browser Forum (CABF).
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] These public root CAs get bundled into trust stores maintained by major browser vendors.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Most things on the web trust these, because someone makes sure the trust stores are where they need to be.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] When an IdP rotates its SAML Signing certificate, each SP must simultaneously update its explicit trust of that certificate.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This can be challenging with only a few SPs.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This pain has led to the use of SAML signing certificates with the longest possible lifetimes.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This used to be two years with public CAs, then 398 days.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The focus of WebPKI standards and the CABF is on server certificates for TLS.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Recent and ongoing changes in certificate lifetimes make Public CA issued certificates less appealing.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is because the CABF has a path to making public CA issued certificates last only 47 days.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] As the IdP must get the certificate, announce the change for a reasonable amount of time, and then execute the change, this would mean IdPs and SPs would be in a perpetual state of certificate updates.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] It is worth noting that the CABF does not have governance around the use or acquisition of SAML certificates, certificates from their member CAs are what are widely considered Public CAs.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] That is, they are widely trusted by browsers, operating systems, and various development frameworks.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Using Public CA signed certificates allows for revocation checking, which can increase security, but if the certificate exchange is not secured, this could lead to a false sense of security.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] As most IdPs and SPs treat the X.509 certificates as an explicit trust, private CAs and PKI could be used.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] How private CAs are designed, built, and run varies wildly and ultimately running CAs well is very costly.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In order to trust a third-party's CAs, one would need to clearly understand the lifecycle of the CA.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] There are two audit types that would cover this, both of which are very costly, on top of building and running the CAs.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If you rely on third-party CAs, they should be WebTrust, ETSI, or SOC 2 Type II audited.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Trusting third-party CAs, if done improperly, could result in unintended over-trust, for things such as TLS and code signing.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If you choose to trust third-party CAs, make sure they are only trusted for the process of IdP signature validation.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If third-party CAs are used they still should not issue SAML signing certificates where the lifetime of the certificate exceeds that of the underlying key pair, based on guidance from a standards organization such as NIST, NSA, etc..
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If using the strongest private key types, this puts the upper limit at two years.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Due to the explicit nature of most SAML security associations, self-signed certificates are ideal for the use case.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The contents of the certificate and lifetime are not constrained by the policy or process of the issuing CA, be it public or private.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] As rotating SAML certificates can be painful and labor intensive, setting the certificate lifetime as long as safely possible is key.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Few CAs allow long enough lifetimes, due to their focus on the TLS threat model.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If you are using a Hardware Security Module (HSM), follow the vendor's instructions.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The example uses an overly generic distinguished name.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Your Common Name (CN) should be meaningful and specific.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Many IdPs publish a metadata URL that contains basic configuration information including the SAML signing certificate.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Many SPs can consume the data from the IdP, updating the Signing certificate information in near real-time.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This model matches exactly the intent of the Certificate and Public Key Pinning when pinning must be used.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The metadata URL should be protected using TLS where the server certificate comes from a WebPKI CA that is widely trusted and matches the guidance in the Transport Layer Security Cheat Sheet.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The ideal state of the IdP to SP relationship is that of using the metadata URLs, regardless of what type of certificate is used.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If metadata URLs are not used, great care must be taken to assure that an attacker does not convince an SP to trust the wrong certificate.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Instead, like the metadata URL, present them over properly configured TLS.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] SAML Signing keys are a top security asset and target of attackers.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Great care should be taken when creating the keys and as needed, copying them to nodes of an IdP cluster.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] File based keys are trivial for an attacker with access to exfiltrate.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] IdP operators should strongly consider protecting the private keys using a Hardware Security Module (HSM).
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] HSMs allow an application to use a key without it being exportable or copyable.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] They have mechanisms to safely replicate the keys into a failover HSM, without ever exposing the keys outside of the HSMs.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Quality HSMs would be rated FIPS 140-2 or FIPS 140-3.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Just because SAML is a security protocol does not mean that input validation goes away.
[src:saml-security/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Solutions relying cryptographic algorithms need to follow the latest developments in cryptoanalysis.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] An important use case that SAML addresses is web-browser single sign-on (SSO).
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Single sign-on is relatively easy to accomplish within a security domain (using cookies, for example) but extending SSO across security domains is more difficult and resulted in the proliferation of non-interoperable proprietary technologies.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The SAML Web Browser SSO profile was specified and standardized to promote interoperability.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] In practice, SAML SSO is most commonly used for authentication into cloud-based business software.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The SAML specification defines three roles: the principal (typically a human user), the identity provider (IdP) and the service provider (SP).
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] In the primary use case addressed by SAML, the principal requests a service from the service provider.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider requests and obtains an authentication assertion from the identity provider.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] On the basis of this assertion, the service provider can make an access control decision, that is, it can decide whether to perform the service for the connected principal.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] At the heart of the SAML assertion is a subject (a principal within the context of a particular security domain) about which something is being asserted.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The subject is usually (but not necessarily) a human.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] As in the SAML 2.0 Technical Overview, the terms subject and principal are used interchangeably.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Before delivering the subject-based assertion from Identity Provider to the Service Provider, the Identity Provider may request some information from the principal (such as a user name and password) in order to authenticate the principal.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML specifies the content of the assertion that is passed from the Identity Provider to the Service Provider.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML, one Identity Provider may provide SAML assertions to many Service Providers.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Similarly, one Service Provider (SP) may rely on and trust assertions from many independent Identity Providers (IdP).
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML does not specify the method of authentication at the identity provider.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The IdP may use a username and password, or some other form of authentication, including multi-factor authentication or Kerberos tickets.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] A directory service such as RADIUS or LDAP that allows users to log in with a user name and password is a typical source of authentication tokens at an identity provider.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The popular Internet social networking services also provide identity services that in theory could be used to support SAML exchanges.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Building on these initial contributions, in November 2002 OASIS announced the Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) 1.0 specification as an OASIS Standard.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Meanwhile, the Liberty Alliance, a large consortium of companies, non-profit and government organizations, proposed an extension to the SAML standard called the Liberty Identity Federation Framework (ID-FF).
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Like its SAML predecessor, Liberty ID-FF proposed a standardized, cross-domain, web-based, single sign-on framework.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] In addition, Liberty described a *circle of trust* where each participating domain is trusted to accurately document the processes used to identify a user, the type of authentication system used, and any policies associated with the resulting authentication credentials.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Other members of the circle of trust could then examine these policies to determine whether to trust such information.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] While Liberty was developing ID-FF, the SSTC began work on a minor upgrade to the SAML standard.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The resulting SAML 1.1 specification was ratified by the SSTC in September 2003.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Then, in November of that same year, Liberty contributed ID-FF 1.2 to OASIS, thereby sowing the seeds for the next major version of SAML.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] In March 2005, SAML 2.0 was announced as an OASIS Standard.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 represents the convergence of Liberty ID-FF and proprietary extensions contributed by the Shibboleth project, as well as early versions of SAML itself.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Most SAML implementations support v2.0 while many still support v1.1 for backward compatibility.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] By January 2008, deployments of SAML 2.0 became common in government, higher education, and commercial enterprises worldwide.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML has undergone one minor and one major revision since 1.0.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Versions 1.0 and 1.1 of SAML are similar even though small differences exist., however, the differences between SAML 2.0 and SAML 1.1 are substantial.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Although the two standards address the same use case, SAML 2.0 is incompatible with its predecessor.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Although ID-FF 1.2 was contributed to OASIS as the basis of SAML 2.0, there are some important differences between SAML 2.0 and ID-FF 1.2.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] In particular, the two specifications, despite their common roots, are incompatible.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML defines XML-based assertions and protocols, bindings, and profiles.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The term *SAML Core* refers to the general syntax and semantics of SAML assertions as well as the protocol used to request and transmit those assertions from one system entity to another.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] *SAML protocol* refers to **what** is transmitted, not **how** (the latter is determined by the choice of binding).
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] So SAML Core defines "bare" SAML assertions along with SAML request and response elements.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] A *SAML binding* determines how SAML requests and responses map onto standard messaging or communications protocols.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] An important (synchronous) binding is the SAML SOAP binding.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] A *SAML profile* is a concrete manifestation of a defined use case using a particular combination of assertions, protocols and bindings.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML assertions are usually transferred from identity providers to service providers.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Assertions contain *statements* that service providers use to make access-control decisions.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] An *attribute statement* asserts that a principal is associated with certain attributes.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] An *attribute* is simply a name–value pair.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Relying parties use attributes to make access-control decisions.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] An *authorization decision statement* asserts that a principal is permitted to perform action *A* on resource *R* given evidence *E*.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The expressiveness of authorization decision statements in SAML is intentionally limited.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] More-advanced use cases are encouraged to use XACML instead.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *protocol* describes how certain SAML elements (including assertions) are packaged within SAML request and response elements, and gives the processing rules that SAML entities must follow when producing or consuming these elements.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] For the most part, a SAML protocol is a simple request-response protocol.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The most important type of SAML protocol request is called a *query*.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] A service provider makes a query directly to an identity provider over a secure back channel.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Thus query messages are typically bound to SOAP.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The result of an attribute query is a SAML response containing an assertion, which itself contains an attribute statement.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] See the SAML 2.0 topic for an example of attribute query/response.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Beyond queries, SAML 1.1 specifies no other protocols.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 expands the notion of *protocol* considerably.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Most of these protocols are new in SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *binding* is a mapping of a SAML protocol message onto standard messaging formats and/or communications protocols.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] For example, the SAML SOAP binding specifies how a SAML message is encapsulated in a SOAP envelope, which itself is bound to an HTTP message.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 1.1 specifies just one binding, the SAML SOAP Binding.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] In addition to SOAP, implicit in SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO are the precursors of the HTTP POST Binding, the HTTP Redirect Binding, and the HTTP Artifact Binding.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] These are not defined explicitly, however, and are only used in conjunction with SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The notion of binding is not fully developed until SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 completely separates the binding concept from the underlying profile.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *profile* describes in detail how SAML assertions, protocols, and bindings combine to support a defined use case.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The most important SAML profile is the Web Browser SSO Profile.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 1.1 specifies two forms of Web Browser SSO, the Browser/Artifact Profile and the Browser/POST Profile.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The latter passes assertions *by value* whereas Browser/Artifact passes assertions *by reference*.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] As a consequence, Browser/Artifact requires a back-channel SAML exchange over SOAP.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML 1.1, all flows begin with a request at the identity provider for simplicity.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Proprietary extensions to the basic IdP-initiated flow have been proposed (by Shibboleth, for example).
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The Web Browser SSO Profile was completely refactored for SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Conceptually, SAML 1.1 Browser/Artifact and Browser/POST are special cases of SAML 2.0 Web Browser SSO.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The latter is considerably more flexible than its SAML 1.1 counterpart due to the new "plug-and-play" binding design of SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Unlike previous versions, SAML 2.0 browser flows begin with a request at the service provider.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] This provides greater flexibility, but SP-initiated flows naturally give rise to the so-called *Identity Provider Discovery* problem, the focus of much research today.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Requirements are often phrased in terms of (mutual) authentication, integrity, and confidentiality, leaving the choice of security mechanism to implementers and deployers.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The primary SAML use case is called *Web Browser Single Sign-On (SSO)*.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] A user utilizes a *user agent* (usually a web browser) to request a web resource protected by a SAML *service provider*.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the requesting user, issues an authentication request to a SAML *identity provider* through the user agent.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The resulting protocol flow is depicted in the following diagram.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The user agent issues a GET request to the SSO service at the URL from step 2.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] URL query parameter) and performs a security check.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The user agent issues a POST request to the assertion consumer service at the service provider.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] parameter is taken from the XHTML form at step 4.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML 1.1, the flow begins with a request to the identity provider's inter-site transfer service at step 3.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] In the example flow above, all depicted exchanges are *front-channel exchanges*, that is, an HTTP user agent (browser) communicates with a SAML entity at each step.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] In particular, there are no *back-channel exchanges* or direct communications between the service provider and the identity provider.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Front-channel exchanges lead to simple protocol flows where all messages are passed *by value* using a simple HTTP binding (GET or POST).
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Indeed, the flow outlined in the previous section is sometimes called the *Lightweight Web Browser SSO Profile*.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Alternatively, for increased security or privacy, messages may be passed *by reference*.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] For example, an identity provider may supply a reference to a SAML assertion (called an *artifact*) instead of transmitting the assertion directly through the user agent.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Subsequently, the service provider requests the actual assertion via a back channel.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Such a back-channel exchange is specified as a SOAP message exchange (SAML over SOAP over HTTP).
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] In general, any SAML exchange over a secure back channel is conducted as a SOAP message exchange.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] On the back channel, SAML specifies the use of SOAP 1.1.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] The use of SOAP as a binding mechanism is optional, however.
[src:saml-security/security-assertion-markup-language] Any given SAML deployment will choose whatever bindings are appropriate.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] XML signatures can be used to sign data–a **resource**–of any type, typically XML documents, but anything that is accessible via a URL can be signed.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] An XML signature used to sign a resource outside its containing XML document is called a detached signature; if it is used to sign some part of its containing document, it is called an **enveloped** signature; if it contains the signed data within itself it is called an **enveloping** signature.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] An XML Signature consists of a `Signature` element in the `http://www.w3.org/2000/09/xmldsig#` namespace.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] When validating an XML Signature, a procedure called **Core Validation** is followed.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] **Signature Validation:** The `SignedInfo` element is serialized using the canonicalization method specified in `CanonicalizationMethod`, the key data is retrieved using `KeyInfo` or by other means, and the signature is verified using the method specified in `SignatureMethod`.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] This procedure establishes whether the resources were really signed by the alleged party.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] Because the signed document's structure can be tampered with leading to "signature wrapping" attacks, the validation process should also cover XML document structure.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] Signed element and signature element should be selected using absolute XPath expression, not `getElementByName` methods.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] The creation of XML Signatures is substantially more complex than the creation of an ordinary digital signature because a given XML Document (an "Infoset", in common usage among XML developers) may have more than one legal serialized representation.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] For example, whitespace inside an XML Element is not syntactically significant, so that `<Elem >` is syntactically identical to `<Elem>`.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] Since the digital signature ensures data integrity, a single-byte difference would cause the signature to vary.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] Moreover, if an XML document is transferred from computer to computer, the line terminator may be changed from CR to LF to CR LF, etc.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] A program that digests and validates an XML document may later render the XML document in a different way, e.g. adding excess space between attribute definitions with an element definition, or using relative (vs. absolute) URLs, or by reordering namespace definitions.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] Canonical XML is especially important when an XML Signature refers to a remote document, which may be rendered in time-varying ways by an errant remote server.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] To avoid these problems and guarantee that logically-identical XML documents give identical digital signatures, an XML canonicalization transform (frequently abbreviated **C14n**) is employed when signing XML documents (for signing the `SignedInfo`, a canonicalization is mandatory).
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] These algorithms guarantee that semantically-identical documents produce exactly identical serialized representations.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] For this reason, the so-called *Exclusive Canonicalization*, which serializes XML namespace declarations independently of the surrounding XML, was created.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] Another core concept is canonicalization, that is to sign only the "essence", eliminating meaningless differences like whitespace and line endings.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] There are criticisms directed at the architecture of XML security in general, and at the suitability of XML canonicalization in particular as a front end to signing and encrypting XML data due to its complexity, inherent processing requirement, and poor performance characteristics.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] The argument is that performing XML canonicalization causes excessive latency that is simply too much to overcome for transactional, performance sensitive SOA applications.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] These issues are being addressed in the XML Security Working Group.
[src:saml-security/xml-signature] Without proper policy and implementation the use of XML Dsig in SOAP and WS-Security can lead to vulnerabilities, such as XML signature wrapping.
